    <h1>Introducing Dot-Public</h1>
    <h2>A digital public space on the internet</h2>

    <p><strong>Dot-Public is conceived not only as a technical architecture</strong>but as a civic institution. Its
        viability depends less on code than on trust, and trust must be earned, demonstrated, and
        protected through governance. The governance framework is therefore not a support act to
        the technical build; it is the decisive factor that will determine whether Dot-Public can endure,
        expand, and remain free of capture.</p>

    <p>It will be governed through a federated, multi-level framework designed to safeguard its
        public purpose, ensure operational resilience, and maintain legitimacy across jurisdictions. It
        will operate as a transnational civic infrastructure while allowing for subsidiarity, national
        legal compatibility, and institutional diversity.</p>

    <h3>Standards</h3>
    <p>As a minimum, all participating services and institutions will be required to meet baseline
        public service obligations, in line with international human rights law and United Nations
        standards, including the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD),
        the UN General Assembly Resolution 78/213, the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable
        Development (notably Goals 4, 9, 10, and 16), and the UN Guiding Principles on Business
        and Human Rights.</p>

    <p>Digital participation will require transparent reporting, alignment with the UNESCO
        Recommendation on Open Science and the UNESCO Guidelines for the Governance of
        Digital Platforms, and compliance with recognised civic standards for privacy, accessibility,
        non-discrimination, and data minimisation.</p>

    <h3>Purpose of governance</h3>
    <p>Governance provides the guardrails within which Dot-Public can operate as a trusted digital
        public space. It is designed to:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>Define the principles and rules of participation</li>
        <li>Ensure transparency in decision-making</li>
        <li>Prevent capture by any state, corporation, or narrow interest</li>
        <li>Maintain the legitimacy of Dot-Public as a public good that benefits everyone and excludes no one.</li>
        <li>Safeguard Dot-Public as a sovereign civic space with a long-term mandate</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Principles</h3>

    <ol>
        <li><strong>Independence</strong>: Dot-Public must be structurally insulated from direct political or
            commercial control.</li>
        <li><strong>Transparency</strong>: All major decisions, rule changes, and operational reports must be
            made public and archived.</li>
        <li><strong>Accountability</strong>: Every decision-making body must be answerable to a higher civic
            forum.</li>
        <li><strong>Inclusion</strong>: Governance must reflect geographic, institutional, and social diversity.</li>
        <li><strong>Subsidiarity</strong>: Decisions should be taken at the most local level possible while
            preserving the integrity of the system.</li>
        <li><strong>Integrity</strong>: No action should compromise civic trust for convenience, growth, or
            revenue.</li>
        <li><strong>Resilience</strong>: Dot-Public must remain forkable and recoverable if governance fails,
            ensuring continuity of civic service.</li>
    </ol>

