    <h3>Funding and sustainability</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>
            Initial funding from philanthropic and public-interest donors, ring-fenced to insulate
            from commercial influence.
        </li>
        <li>
            Long-term sustainability through member contributions scaled to institutional size,
            plus limited revenue from accreditation services.
        </li>
        <li>
            Explicit prohibition on advertising, monetisation of user data (without a subject
            fiduciary involved), or profit distribution.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Permitted revenue generation</h3>
    <p>Revenue generation within Dot-Public must be transparent, mission-aligned, and free from
        hidden incentives. Participating institutions and publishers may generate income through the
        following permitted means:</p>

    <ol>
        <li><strong>Subscriptions and access fees</strong> - Institutions may charge for direct access to their
            own material or services, provided the terms are clear and non-discriminatory.</li>
        <li><strong>Pay-per-view or pay-per-read</strong> - One-off access charges are allowed where
            appropriate to cover costs and generate income.</li>
        <li><strong>Contextual display advertising</strong> - Ads must be proportionate and secondary to the
            civic purpose of the service. Any data-driven, targeted advertising must be approved
            by someone (including automated agents) having a duty of care and loyalty to the
            person whose attention is being sought. Thus, static, clearly labelled advertising in
            the style of pre-digital newspaper or broadcast ads is permitted. Advertising that
            relies on personal data, tracking, or behavioural profiling will need a fiduciary of the
            citizen in the loop. Contextual display advertising – Static, clearly labelled advertising
            in the style of pre-digital newspaper or broadcast ads is permitted, provided it does
            not rely on personal data, tracking, or behavioural profiling. Ads must be
            proportionate and secondary to the civic purpose of the service.</li>
        <li><strong>Institutional contributions</strong> - Members contribute scaled fees to support the shared
            infrastructure, ensuring sustainability without dependence on commercial influence.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Explicitly prohibited are revenue models that rely on profiling, behavioural targeting, resale of
        user data, or covert sponsorships that would compromise trust.</p>

    <h3>Public accountability</h3>
    <ol>
        <li>An annual Civic Assembly is held in open session, allowing the wider public and civil
            society groups to scrutinise performance.</li>
        <li>All documentation is preserved in a publicly accessible archive.[CLOCKSS?]</li>
        <li>Civic metrics (trust surveys, accessibility reports, audit outcomes) are published
            annually as the key measure of success.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Dot-Public will not be state-run, nor centralised under a single authority. Its design
        recognises the complexity of digital governance, and ensures democratic legitimacy by
        embedding accountability at each level – from citizen feedback platforms to national audits
        and service-wide performance reviews.</p>

    <p>Legitimacy will rest not on political appointment or market dominance, but on its civic
        mandate and enforceable values. Technical delivery may be managed by a nonprofit entity
        operating under contract, but ultimate responsibility will reside with the network of
        accountable public bodies that comprise the [Dot-Public Federation?].</p>

    <p>This structure ensures that Dot-Public can grow as a trusted, pluralistic infrastructure,
        coordinated at scale, but rooted in national legal traditions and democratic oversight.</p>
